\begin_layout Subsubsection
Company categorization and strategies 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the size of the company relative to others in a particular industry
 is established, the next step is to place it into one of six general categories
 (there are many other possible ways of classifying stocks, but these should
 cover all useful distinctions that any investor has to make):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Slow growers (low risk, low gain)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Usually large and aging companies, they are expected to grow slightly faster
 than the GNP.
 They didn't start out that way.
 They started as fast growers and eventually pooped out - maybe they had
 gone as far as they could, or else they got too tired to make the most
 of their changes.
 When an industry at large slows down (as they always seem to do), most
 of the companies within the industry lose momentum as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sooner or later every popular fast-growing industry becomes a slow-growing
 industry, and numerous analysts are fooled.
 There is always a tendency to think that things will never change, but
 inevitably they do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Another sign of a slow grower is that it pays a generous and regular dividend.
 Companies pay generous dividends when they can't dream up new ways to use
 the money to expand the business.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We won't find a lot of 2-4% growers in Lynch's portfolio, because if companies
 aren't going anywhere fast, neither will the price of their stocks.
 If growth in earnings is what enriches a company, then what's the sense
 of wasting time on slow growers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you start thinking about slow grower, it's probably for its dividends,
 so you have to carefully check whether a company can give you them in the
 future.
 Also payout ratio - low % means that the company has a cushion in hard
 times.
 It can earn less money and still retain the dividend.
 If the percentage is higher, the dividend is riskier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Selling
\series default
 - if the price goes up by 30-50%, the company has lost market share for
 2 consecutive years, no new products are being developed, spending on research
 and development is curtailed, and the company appears to be resting on
 its laurels.
 Two recent acquisitions of unrelated business look like diworsefications
 and the company announces it is looking for further acquisitions "at the
 leading edge of technology".
 The company has paid so much for its acquisitions that the balance sheet
 has deteriorated from no debt and millions in cash to no cash and millions
 in debt.
 Even at a lower stock price the dividend yield will not be high enough
 to attract much interest from investors.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Stalwarts (low risk, moderate gain)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
These are companies such as Coca-Cola.
 These multibillion-dollar hulks are not exactly agile climbers, but they're
 faster than slow growers.
 These have 10-12% annual growth in earnings.
 Depending on when you buy them and at what price, you can make a sizable
 profit in stalwarts.
 But it depends on how long it can take to make some money on a given stalwart.
 If you own a stalwart and the stock's gone up 50% in a year or two, you
 have to wonder if maybe that's enough and begin to think about selling.
 How much you can expect to squeeze out of Colgate-Palmolive? You aren't
 going to become a millionaire off it the way you could with fast growers,
 unless there is some startling new development.
 Fifty percent in two years is what you'd be delighted to get from stalwart
 in most normal situations.
 With stalwarts you have to consider taking profits more readily.
 They are stocks that Lynch generally buys for a 30-50% gain, then sell
 and repeat the process with similar issues that haven't yet appreciated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lynch always keeps some stalwarts in his portfolio because they offer pretty
 good protection during recessions and hard times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you start thinking about stalwart, then the key issues are the price,
 P/E ratio, whether the stock already has had a dramatic run-up in price
 in recent months, and what, if anything, is happening to accelerate the
 growth rate.
 Also check the company's long term growth rate, and whether it has kept
 up the same momentum in recent years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you're planning to keep the company forever, see how the company has
 fared during previous recessions and market drops.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Selling
\series default
 - rotating them frequently with others in the category.
 There is no point in expecting a quick tenbagger in a stalwart, and if
 the stock price gets above the earnings line, or if the p/e strays too
 far beyond the normal range, you might think about selling it and waiting
 to buy it back later at a lower price - or buying something else.
 New products introduced in the last 2 years have had mixed results, and
 others still in the testing stage are a year away from the marketplace.
 The stock has a P/E of 15 while similar-quality companies in the industry
 have P/E of 11-12.
 No officers or directors have bought shares in the last year.
 A major division that contributes 25% of earnings is vulnerable to an economic
 slump that's taking place.
 The company's growth rate has been slowing down, and though it's been maintaini
ng profits by cutting costs, future cost-cutting opportunities are limited.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Fast growers (high gain, high risk)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
These are small, aggressive new enterprises that grow at 20-25% a year.
 If you choose wisely, this is the land of 10-40 baggers, and even 200-baggers.
 Fast-growing company doesn't necessarily have to belong to a fast growing
 industry.
 Actually, Lynch prefers slower industries.
 These enterprises learned to succeed in one place, and hen to duplicate
 the winning formula over and over, mall by mall, city by city.
 The expansion into new markets results in the phenomenal acceleration in
 earnings that drives the stock price to the highs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is plenty of risk in fast growers, especially in he younger companies
 that tend to be overzealous and under-financed.
 Also, Wall Street does not look kindly on fast growers that run out of
 stamina and turn into slow growers, and when that happens, the stocks are
 beaten down accordingly.
 While slow fast growers risk extinction, the larger fast growers risk a
 rapid devaluation when they begin to falter.
 Once a fast grower gets too big, there is simply no place for it to stretch
 out.
 But for as long as they can keep it up, fast growers are the big winners
 in the stock market.
 Look for good balance sheets and those that are making substantial profits.
 The trick is to figuring out when they'll stop growing, and how much to
 pay for the growth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you start thinking about fast grower, then where and how can it continue
 to grow? Can it successfully duplicate its business model in another city
 or state - did it already proven? What about debt and niche? Does the idea
 work elsewhere? Does the product that's supposed to enrich the company
 is a major part of the company's business? What the growth rate in earnings
 has been in recent years (20-25% are the best).
 Lynch is worried about companies with the growth faster than 25%.
 Those 50% are usually in hot industries, that can drop down very quickly.
 Is there still a room to grow? Is the stock selling at a P/E ratio at or
 near the growth rate?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Selling
\series default
 - the trick here is not to lose the potential tenbagger.
 The main thing to watch for is the end of the second phase of rapid growth.
 Unlike the cyclical where the P/E ratio gets smaller near the end, in a
 growth company the P/E usually gets bigger, and it may reach absurd and
 illogical dimensions.
 Same store sales are down 3% in the last quarter.
 New store results are disappointing.
 Top executives or key employees leave to join a rival firm.
 The stock is selling at a P/E of 30, while the most optimistic projections
 of earnings growth are 15-20% for the next 2 years.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Cyclicals (low risk and high gain, or high risk and low gain, depending
 on how adept you are at anticipating cycles)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
These are companies whose sales and profits rise and fall in regular if
 not completely predictable fashion.
 In a growth industry, business jut keeps expanding, but in a cyclical industry,
 it expands and contracts, then expands and contracts again.
 Autos, airlines, tire companies, steel companies, chemical companies are
 all cyclicals.
 For example Ford is a cyclical.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Coming out of a recession and into a vigorous economy, the cyclicals flourish
 and their stock prices tend to rise much faster than the price of the stalwarts.
 This is understandable, since people buy new cars and take more airplane
 trips in a vigorous economy, and there's greater demand for steel, chemicals,
 etc.
 But going other direction, you can lose more than 50% of your investment
 very quickly if you buy cyclicals in the wrong part of the cycle, and it
 may be years before you'll see another upswing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cyclicals are the most misunderstood of all the types of stocks.
 It is here that the unwary stock-picker is most easily parted from his
 money, and in stocks that he considers safe.
 Because the major cyclicals are large and well-known companies, they are
 naturally lumped together with the trusty stalwarts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Timing is everything in cyclicals, and you have to be able to detect the
 early signs that business is falling off or picking up.
 It's really good to have an edge when investing into cyclicals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you start thinking about cyclical company, then you think about business
 conditions, inventories, and prices.
 Keep a close watch on inventories and supply-demand relationship.
 Watch for new entrants into the market, which is usually a dangerous developmen
t.
 Anticipate a shrinking P/E over time as business recovers and investors
 look ahead to the end of the cycle, then peak earnings are achieved.
 Try to figure out the end of the cycle, there always are.
 It is much easier to predict an upturn in a cyclical industry than it is
 to predict a downturn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Selling
\series default
 - The best time is toward the end of the cycle, but it's difficult to do.
 Rising inventories, falling commodity prices, of the future price of a
 commodity is lower than the current price.
 Competition businesses.
 Final demand for the product is slowing down.
 The company has tried to cut costs but still can't compete with foreign
 producers.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Asset plays (low risk, moderate-high gain, if you are sure of the value
 of the assets)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This is any company that's sitting on something valuable that you know about,
 but that the Wall Street crowd has overlooked.
 Local edge can be used to greatest advantage.
 The asset may be as simple as a pile of cash.
 Sometimes it's real estate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Asset opportunities are everywhere.
 They require a working knowledge of a company that owns the assets, but
 once that's understood, all you need is patience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you start thinking about asset play, then you have to determine what
 are the assets and how much are they worth.
 Is the company taking on new debt, making the assets less valuable?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It's hard for amateurs to find a good asset stock!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Selling
\series default
 - The institutional ownership has risen from 25% five years ago to 60%
 today.
 The reduction in the corporate tax rate considerably reduces the value
 of the company's tax-loss carry forward.
 The division that was expected to be sold for $20 million only brings $12
 million in the actual sale.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Turnarounds (high gain, high risk)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
They are battered and depressed.
 These are not slow growers, these are no growers.
 These aren't cyclicals that rebound, these are potential fatalities.
 These can be ex-cyclicals that went so far down in a down cycle that people
 think that it can never come back up.
 A poorly managed cyclical is always a potential candidate for the kind
 of trouble that can end up being a fatality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These stocks make up lost ground very quickly.
 The best thing about investing in successful turnarounds is that of all
 the categories of stocks, their ups and downs are least related to the
 general market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the absolute dollars, Lynch get his greatest profits from the revival
 of turnarounds.
 But he also bought lots of companies that went bankrupt.
 In spite of this, the occasional major success makes the turnaround business
 very exciting and very rewarding as well.
 But be careful and try to stay away from the tragedies where the outcome
 is unmeasurable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are many kinds of turnarounds.
 For example, there are perfectly-good-company-inside-a-bankrupt-companies.
 Or, the restructuring-to-maximize-shareholder-values kind of turnaround.
 Restructuring is a company's way of ridding itself of certain unprofitable
 subsidiaries it should never have acquired in the first place.
 Lynch calls it diworsification.
 The only positive aspect is that some companies that diworsefy themselves
 into sorry shape are future candidates for turnarounds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you start thinking about turnaround, then you are asking questions about
 - has the company gone about improving its fortunes and is the plan working
 so far? Can the company survive a raid by its creditors? How much cash
 it has? How much debt? What is the debt structure? How long it can operate
 while working out its problems without going bankrupt? How the company
 is supposed to be turning around? Has it rid itself of unprofitable divisions?
 Are costs being cut? If so, what will the effect be?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Selling
\series default
 - Debt, which has declined for 5 straight quarters, just those in the latest
 quarterly report.
 Inventories are rising at twice the rate of sales growth.
 The P/E is inflated relative to earnings prospects.
 The company's strongest division sells 50% of its output to one leading
 customer, and that leading customer is suffering from a slowdown in its
 own sales.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Companies don't stay in the same category forever.
 Some companies can fall into two categories at once.
 Disney has been in all category over its lifetime.
 Also, putting stocks in categories is the first step in developing the
 story!! Now at least you know what kind of story it's supposed to be.
 The next step is filling the details that will help you guess how the story
 is going to turn out.
 Getting the story is a lot easier if you understand the basic business.
 Simpler it is, the better.
 When somebody says "Any idiot could run it", then it's a plus, because
 sooner or later any idiot probably is going to be running it.
 If it's a choice between owning stock in a fine company with excellent
 management in a highly competitive and complex industry, or a humdrum company
 with mediocre management in a simpleminded industry with no competition,
 Lynch would prefer the latter.
 "Any idiot can run this business" is one characteristic of the perfect
 company, the kind of stock Lynch wants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So firstly you decided what category a stock is in, then P/E ratio (check
 Chapter Valuation) has given you a rough idea of whether the stock is currently
 roughly undervalued or overvalued, and then the next step for Lynch is
 to learn as much possible about what the company is doing.
 It's story must be developed.
\end_layout

