\begin_layout Paragraph
Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Howard Marks: understand it, recognize it when it's high, and control it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Riskier investments involve greater uncertainty regarding the outcome, as
 well as the increased likelihood of some painful ones.
 So riskier investments are those for which the outcome is less certain.
 That is, the probability distribution of returns is wider.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Risk is the likelihood of losing money.
 The possibility of permanent capital loss is the only risk to worry about.
 Risk means uncertainty about which outcome will occur and about the possibility
 of loss when the unfavorable ones do.
 Risk exists only in the future, and it's impossible to know for sure what
 the future holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Return alone - and especially return over short periods of time - says very
 little about the quality of investment decisions.
 Return has to be evaluated relative to the amount of risk taken to achieve
 it.
 And yet, risk cannot be measured.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
"The greatest risk doesn't come from low quality or high volatility It comes
 from paying prices that are too high.
 This isn't a theoretical risk; it's very real."
\emph default
 High price both increases risk and lowers returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Given the difficulty of quantifying the probability of loss, investors who
 want some objective measure of risk-adjusted return - and they are many
 - can only look to the so-called Sharpe ratio.
 It's the ratio of a portfolio's excess return (its return above "risk-less
 rate" - rate of short-term Treasury bills) to the standard deviation of
 the return.
 According to Howard Marks, it's the best we have.
 While it says nothing explicitly about the likelihood of loss, there may
 be reason to believe that the prices of fundamentally riskier securities
 fluctuate more than those of safer ones, and thus the Sharpe ratio has
 some relevance.
 However, it doesn't do a good job of measuring risk of future loss.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Worry and its relatives, distrust, skepticism and risk aversion are essential
 ingredients in a safe financial system.
 Worry keeps risky loans from being made, companies from taking on more
 debt than they can service, portfolios from becoming overly concentrated,
 and unproven schemes from turning into popular manias.
 When risk aversion are present as they should be, investors will question,
 investigate and act prudently.
 Investment risk comes primarily from too-high prices, and too-high prices
 often come from excessive optimism and inadequate skepticism and risk aversion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Risk arises as investor behavior alters the market.
 Investors bid up assets, accelerating into the present appreciation that
 otherwise would have occurred in the future, and thus lowering prospective
 returns.
 And as their psychology strengthens and they become bolder and less worried,
 investors cease to demand adequate risk premiums.
 The ultimate irony lies in the fact that the reward for taking incremental
 risk shrinks as more people move to take it.
 Thus, the market is not a static arena in which investors operate.
 It is responsive, shaped by investors' own behavior.
 Their increasing confidence creates more that they should worry about,
 just as their rising fear and risk aversion combine to widen risk premiums
 at the same time as they reduce risk.
 "I wouldn't buy that at any price - everyone knows it's too risky." That's
 something Howard has heard a lot in his life, and it has given rise to
 the best investment opportunities he has participated in.
 The truth is, the herd is wrong about risk at least as often as it is about
 return.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Risk may have been present even though loss didn't occur.
 Therefore, the absence of loss does not necessarily mean the portfolio
 was safely constructed.
 The risk control is invisible in good times but still essential, since
 good times can so easily turn into bad times.
 Loss is what happens when risk meets adversity.
 Risk gives rise to loss only when negative events occur in the environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A good builder is able to avoid construction flaws, while a poor builder
 incorporates construction flaws.
 When there are no earthquakes, you can't tell the difference.
 Likewise, an excellent investor may be one who - rather than reporting
 higher returns than others - achieves the same return but does so with
 less risk (or even achieves a slightly lower return with far less risk).
 Controlling the risk in your portfolio is a very important and worth-while
 pursuit.
 The fruits, however, come only in the form of losses than don't happen.
 Such what-if calculations are difficult in placid times.
 This is the ultimate paradox of risk management.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Risk control is the best route to loss avoidance.
 Risk avoidance, on the other hand, is likely to lead to return avoidance
 as well.
 The road to long-term investment success runs through risk control more
 than through aggressiveness.
 Over a full career, most investors' results will be determined more by
 how many losers they have, and how bad they are, than by the greatness
 of their winners.
 Skillful risk control is the mark of the superior investor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Investment risk resides most where it is least perceived, and vice versa:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
When everyone believes something is risky, their unwillingness to buy usually
 reduces its price to the point where it's not risky at all.
 Broadly negative opinion can make if the least risky thing, since all optimism
 has been driven out of its price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And, of course, as demonstrated by the experience of Nifty Fifty investors,
 when everyone believes something embodies no risk, they usually bid it
 up to the point where it's enormously risky.
 No risk is feared, and thus no reward for risk bearing - no "risk premium"
 - is demanded or provided.
 That can make the thing that's most esteemed the riskiest.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
William O'Neil
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Founder of Investor's Business Daily, national competitor of The Wall Street
 Journal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
He created a system for finding growth stocks called CAN SLIM.
 O'Neil stresses that every one of the attributes must apply to a company
 for him to invest in it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
C: Current quarterly earnings per share should be accelerating.
 It should be increased compared to the same quarter from the prior year.
 "The percentage increase in earnings per share is the single most important
 element in stock selection today." Bigger increases are better than the
 little ones, but investors should be careful not to be misled by huge increases
 over tiny ones from the previous year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A: Annual earnings per share should be accelerating.
